{#
  Shared status chip — Wave 1 of the UI redesign (2026-06-03).

  Single chip system that supersedes the four overlapping families
  currently in use (.tag with pos/neg/warn, .chip with pos/warn/bad,
  .pill with ok/bad/warn, .fraud-chip). Wave 2 templates can adopt
  this partial directly; the legacy classes continue to render
  unchanged until a future sweep (backlog item:
  project-chip-canonical-name-sweep) migrates all callers.

  This partial renders as a <span class="chip {{ tone-class }}"> so
  it reuses the existing .chip styling in aegis-tool.css :297-332.
  The tone mapping uses the LEGACY .chip variant names so the visual
  is identical to what's already on the page; the SEMANTIC name lives
  in the `tone` input.

  Inputs:
    tone  — one of: "good" | "warn" | "bad" | "info" | "neutral"
            (canonical names; mapped to legacy .chip class below)
    label — the chip's visible text (string, required)
    title — optional tooltip text (string, optional)

  Tone → legacy class mapping (Wave 1; identical computed styles):
    good    → .chip.pos       (uses --approve)
    warn    → .chip.warn      (uses --review)
    bad     → .chip.bad       (uses --decline)
    info    → .chip.info      (uses --accent)
    neutral → .chip (no variant; uses --ink-3 via base style)

  Reason-aware variants (e.g. merchant.needs_manual_naming) belong
  in the calling template — pass `label` constructed from the audit
  details `reason` so the operator sees the specific cause.
#}
{%- set _tone_class = {
    "good": "pos",
    "warn": "warn",
    "bad": "bad",
    "info": "info",
    "neutral": ""
}.get(tone, "") -%}
<span class="chip{% if _tone_class %} {{ _tone_class }}{% endif %}"{% if title %} title="{{ title }}"{% endif %}>{{ label }}</span>
